  "prompt": "Is it possible to go faster than the speed of light?",
  "response": "As of current scientific understanding, it is not possible to travel faster than the speed of light. According to Einstein's theory of relativity, the speed of light in a vacuum (approximately 299,792 kilometers per second) is the ultimate speed limit for the universe. Objects with mass require infinite energy to reach the speed of light, making it theoretically impossible for them to travel at or exceed this speed.\n\nHowever, scientists continue to explore theoretical possibilities and concepts in physics, such as wormholes or the hypothetical particles known as tachyons, which could provide ways to circumvent this limitation. These ideas remain speculative and have not been experimentally validated. Therefore, faster-than-light travel remains a topic of theoretical investigation rather than practical reality.",
